The paper deals with the analysis of cooperative cellular networks using stochastic geometry, which is a common approach in the field of information theory (cs.IT). The focus is on the network performance and coverage probability, which are typical topics in the subfield of networking and internet architecture (cs.NI). The cooperation models involve the exchange of user data and channel information, which requires coordination and control, making it relevant to the subfield of control systems (cs.SY). The use of geometric policies to direct user decisions is related to the subfield of machine learning (cs.MA). Finally, the analysis of network problems and optimization can be seen as a topic in game theory (cs.GT).
